rComments: Nothing special but nothing boring. Tried to be funny, but awkward at times. Lectures were manageable though, just do not have two iclickers because he has the eyes of a hawk and will catch you.

His lectures aren't really helpful to be honest. And he doesn't explain the lecture slide problems clearly. But he loves doing demonstrations in class, and is really passionate about his work. I guess it sort of balances out? Do past exams rigorously and you'll be fine.

Pretty good lecture, kind of boring but that's because the material is dull.  You can tell he's really passionate about the subject and is super energetic.  Really good at answering students questions in class too.

Really great professor, honestly. If you are confused, he is really helpful in office hours. He makes his lectures interesting. Expect quizzes every week and hw twice a week. Pro tip: He will put the in class questions most people got wrong on the exams. And on the final he puts questions that the most people got wrong each test.

You will only lose points on exams and quizzes, that being said,  make sure you study and understand the materially and you'll be fine. Tests were made harder than intended but were curved as compensation.

A very sweet guy, classes are somewhat helpful but always interesting with constant demonstrations, many of which he fails in a "Looney Tunes" sort of way, or wows the audience with the result. He does demand that no one is on his or her cellcomputer, and will stop lecture until everyone is paying attention, however.

Gollin is a good guy and he does care for his students. However, not the best lecturer; has the strangest anecdotes, does demonstrations that aren't even related to the material and can ramble about concepts. That being said, tests are fair and can be challenging. If you study, do the homework and labs, you should be fine.

He really likes teaching and it shows. He cares about your understanding. I will say that sometimes his explanations for tougher concepts went over my head. He also had end-of-semester BBQs that were pretty fun. He's a great cook, and full of stories.
Gollin makes lectures very entertaining. Although you just go over what you did on the pre-lectures.
George is the man!  Make sure to attend the BBQs.

The most important thing for study his pays211 is watching the prelecture. Because he didn't teach anything useful in the class. And the homework is really hard. But exam is relative easy. Hope he can teach us physics not just jokes in class.

Fun, engaging lectures. Better than Adshead. The material was easy and he explained most problems clearly.    Midterm 1: easy (A) Midterm 2: moderately difficult (A-) Midterm 3: easy (A+) Final: moderately easy (A)

Gollin is not the best lecturer and sometimes gets confused by his own demo set-ups. If you're taking 211 with Gollin, be prepared to watch and rewatch the prelecture videos before exams because the lectures are pretty much full of useless proofs and him messing up lab demonstrations.
He is a nice, funny guy and is ready to help. Though he is not the best lecturer, but the prelecture videos made this up.

George Gollin is the best physics professor I have ever taken. While not the greatest lecturer, he more than makes up for it with an outstanding course setup that is geared to help you succeed. The homework is not only hilarious, but is great at helping you learn the material. The tests aren't timed. So if you know the material, you will do well.

He is definitely the best physics professor I have ever had. He's not the best lecturer, but will do anything individually to help students understand. He definitely makes the class challenging, but in a good way. He makes you think, and helps you understand how if you go to office hours and what not. Loved this guy.

Gollin was my professor for both PHYS 325 & 326. Never was there a textbook. Instead he hand wrote all the notes for the class. They were more helpful then any book I've read. Office hours are a huge help, he ensures that everyone can make at least one. He also taught us GR. Just because. Homework was worth a lot in the class, good grades possible

One of the best teachers I've ever had. Cares deeply about his students and the material. The tests and hw are usually difficult, but are always relevant and he'll bend over backwards to help you understand it. Highly recommended for the 325/6 sequence.

As the first upper division physics class many undergraduate physicists take, I would highly recommend Professor Gollin for PHYS 325.  He is very helpful and is always open for office hours.

Inspiring, animated, difficult.  This man loves teaching and will do anything he can to help you do as well as possible, except write an easy test!
